**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- Uses a fast general-purpose hash (SHA-256) instead of a slow, memory-hard password hashing function, making brute-force cheap.
- Omits a unique per-user salt, allowing use of precomputed rainbow tables and enabling attackers to crack many hashes at once.
